## Testing Mock Platform

The Testing sub-tree provides a complete set of stub implementations allowing the full application lifecycle and all ECS systems to run inside unit tests without a Win32 window or a DirectX device.

All Testing types are compiled only when the preprocessor symbol `TESTS_ENABLED` is defined (the `Testing` CMake configuration passes `-DTESTS_ENABLED` to every target).

### `pg::TestingWindow`

```cpp
class TestingWindow : public Window {
public:
    TestingWindow(const WindowProps& props);  // no-op constructor
    ~TestingWindow();
    void OnUpdate() override;         // no-op
    void Shutdown() override;         // no-op
    unsigned int GetWidth() const override  { return 0; }
    unsigned int GetHeight() const override { return 0; }
    void SetVSync(bool enabled) override {}
    bool IsVSync() const override { return false; }
    void* GetNativeWindow() const override   { return nullptr; }
    void* GetGraphicsContext() const override { return nullptr; }

    // Test-only: fires an event directly through the Application's callback
    void TESTING_TriggerEvent(pg::Event* event);
};
```

`TESTING_TriggerEvent` calls `m_Data.EventCallback(*event)` directly, bypassing the Win32 message loop entirely. Tests use this to inject `WindowCloseEvent`, `KeyPressedEvent`, mouse events, etc. into the running application without any OS involvement.

`TestingWindow.cpp` also provides the `#ifdef TESTS_ENABLED` guarded definitions of `Window::m_Data` and `Window::Create()`:

```cpp
#ifdef TESTS_ENABLED
pg::Window::Data pg::Window::m_Data;
pg::S_Ptr<pg::Window> pg::Window::Create(const pg::WindowProps& props)
{
    return std::make_unique<pg::TestingWindow>(props);
}
#endif
```

### `pg::TestingInput`

```cpp
class TestingInput : public PlatformInput {
protected:
    bool IsKeyPressedImpl(int keycode) override;      // searches TESTING_KeysPressed
    bool IsMouseButtonPressedImpl(int button) override; // searches TESTING_MouseButtonKeysPressed
    std::pair<float, float> GetMousePositionImpl() override; // returns TESTING_MousePos
    float GetMouseXImpl() override;
    float GetMouseYImpl() override;
    unsigned char GetKeyCodeImpl(unsigned char keyCode) override;      // identity (returns keyCode)
    unsigned char GetMouseButtonCodeImpl(unsigned char keyCode) override; // identity

public:
    std::vector<int> TESTING_KeysPressed;
    std::vector<int> TESTING_MouseButtonKeysPressed;
    std::pair<float, float> TESTING_MousePos;
};
```

The identity implementation of `GetKeyCodeImpl` and `GetMouseButtonCodeImpl` is the key difference from `WindowsInput`: because tests inject events using engine `PG_KEY_*` codes directly (not Win32 VK codes), no translation is needed.

Tests cast the `PlatformInput` singleton to `TestingInput*` to set the public `TESTING_*` members before exercising systems that query input state.

### `pg::TestingContext`

A no-op `GraphicsContext`. Constructor accepts an `HWND` (to match the `Dx11Context` signature) but ignores it. All methods — `Init`, `Shutdown`, `SwapBuffers`, `SetSize` — are no-ops. `GetWidth()` and `GetHeight()` always return `0`.

### `pg::TestingRendererAPI`

A near-no-op `RendererAPI`. The only meaningful implementation is `Begin()`, which clears all tracking collections inside `TestingHelper::GetInstance()`:
- `m_VertexBuffer`, `m_VertexBufferBind`, `m_VertexBufferUnbind`
- `m_VertexBufferSetVertices`, `m_VertexBufferAppendVertices`
- `m_IndexBuffer`, `m_IndexBufferBind`, `m_IndexBufferUnbind`
- `m_IndexBufferSetIndices`, `m_IndexBufferAppendIndices`

All other methods (`Init`, `SetViewport`, `SetClearColor`, `End`, `Clear`, `DrawIndexed`) are empty.

### `pg::TestingBuffer`

`TestingVertexBuffer` and `TestingIndexBuffer` record every operation in `TestingHelper`:
- Constructor: pushes `this` onto `m_VertexBuffer` / `m_IndexBuffer`.
- `Bind()`: pushes onto `m_VertexBufferBind` / `m_IndexBufferBind`.
- `Unbind()`: pushes onto `m_VertexBufferUnbind` / `m_IndexBufferUnbind`.
- `SetVertices` / `AppendVertices`: copies vertex data into `TestingHelper::m_Vertices[20000]` using `memcpy` at a stride of `10 * sizeof(float)` per vertex, and records metadata in `m_VertexBufferSetVertices` / `m_VertexBufferAppendVertices`.
- `SetIndices` / `AppendIndices`: analogous, writes into `TestingHelper::m_Indices[20000]`.

`TestingConstantBuffer<T>` is a template stub with an empty constructor and a no-op `Bind(UINT slot)`.

### `pg::TestingShader`

All uniform-upload methods are no-ops. The shader stores the name passed to the constructor in `TEST_Name` (public member) so test assertions can verify which shader was bound. `Bind()` and `Unbind()` are no-ops.

### `pg::TestingTexture2D` / `pg::TestingTexture2DArray`

`TestingTexture2D` reads two static members, `s_ExpectedWidth` and `s_ExpectedHeight` (both `uint32_t`, default `0`), and stores them in the base `Texture::Data m_Data`. This allows tests that exercise texture coordinate calculations (`GetTexCoordsRect`) to set expected dimensions before constructing the texture.

`GetTexCoordsRect` performs a real calculation: normalises pixel offset and size by `s_ExpectedWidth` / `s_ExpectedHeight` and returns a `glm::vec4(u0, v0, u1, v1)`.

`TestingTexture2DArray` is entirely empty — constructor, `Append`, `Bind`, `GetCount`, `GetMaxCount` are all no-ops or return `0`.

### `pg::TestingHelper`

A singleton observation log. Tests call `TestingHelper::GetInstance()` to inspect recorded renderer operations.

```cpp
class TestingHelper {
public:
    static TestingHelper& GetInstance();
    static void Reset();   // replaces s_Instance with a fresh default-constructed one

    // VertexBuffer tracking
    std::vector<const TestingVertexBuffer*> m_VertexBuffer;
    std::vector<const TestingVertexBuffer*> m_VertexBufferBind;
    std::vector<const TestingVertexBuffer*> m_VertexBufferUnbind;
    std::vector<VertexBufferSetVerticesData> m_VertexBufferSetVertices;
    std::vector<VertexBufferSetVerticesData> m_VertexBufferAppendVertices;

    // IndexBuffer tracking
    std::vector<const TestingIndexBuffer*> m_IndexBuffer;
    std::vector<const TestingIndexBuffer*> m_IndexBufferBind;
    std::vector<const TestingIndexBuffer*> m_IndexBufferUnbind;
    std::vector<IndexBufferSetVerticesData> m_IndexBufferSetIndices;
    std::vector<IndexBufferSetVerticesData> m_IndexBufferAppendIndices;

    float    m_Vertices[20000];
    uint32_t m_Indices[20000];
private:
    static pg::S_Ptr<TestingHelper> s_Instance;
};
```

`Reset()` is called from `pg::CreateApplication()` in `Code/UT/Utils/TestApp.cpp` at the start of each test to ensure a clean tracking state.

