## Non-Obvious Design Decisions

**`Window::m_Data` is static and shared.** The `Window::Data` struct (holding the title and the event callback) is declared `protected static` on the base class and defined in exactly one platform translation unit. This means only one `Window` instance can exist at a time per process, which is fine since the engine creates a single window, but makes the design fragile if multiple windows were ever needed.

**`Window::Create` and `PlatformInput::s_Instance` are selected at link time, not runtime.** There is no runtime flag, registry entry, or configuration file consulted. The `#ifdef TESTS_ENABLED` guards are evaluated at compile time in the respective `.cpp` files. Switching platform implementations requires a different build configuration.

**`WindowProc` is static.** The class has no `this` pointer in `WindowProc`. The per-instance `HWND` and `GraphicsContext` are therefore not accessible from inside the message handler (beyond what is stored in the static `m_WindowsData`). Event callbacks are reached through the static `m_Data.EventCallback`, which is why `m_Data` must be static.

**ImGui input precedes engine input.** `WindowProc` calls `ImGui_ImplWin32_WndProcHandler` first, before `ProcessEvent`. If ImGui returns `true` (meaning it consumed the event), `ProcessEvent` is skipped entirely. Keyboard and mouse events captured by ImGui do not reach the engine event bus and therefore do not appear in `InputStateSingletonComponent`.

**`WM_DESTROY` returns `false` from `ProcessEvent`.** All other messages return `true` (falling through to `DefWindowProc`). `WM_DESTROY` returns `false`, bypassing `DefWindowProc`, because `PostQuitMessage(0)` has already been called and no default processing is needed.

**Key-repeat detection uses bit 30 of `lParam`.** `ProcessKeyDownEvent` reads `lParam & 0x40000000` to distinguish an initial key press from an auto-repeat. The `KeyPressedEvent` repeat count is `0` for a new press and `1` for any repeat, not the actual repeat count that Win32 encodes in the low 16 bits of `lParam`.

**`TestingInput` uses identity code mapping.** Unlike `WindowsInput`, which translates Win32 VK codes to engine `PG_KEY_*` codes, `TestingInput::GetKeyCodeImpl` and `GetMouseButtonCodeImpl` return the input unchanged. Tests therefore inject event components using `PG_KEY_*` values directly, and `InputSystem` — which calls `PlatformInput::GetKeyCode()` — gets back the same value with no translation loss.

**`TestingTexture2D` dimensions are driven by static state.** `TestingTexture2D::s_ExpectedWidth` and `s_ExpectedHeight` are static members set by the test before constructing a texture. Both constructor overloads (from path and from raw data) ignore their arguments and use these statics. This allows tests to exercise `GetTexCoordsRect` with known dimensions without having a real image loader.

**`TestingRendererAPI::Begin()` is the test-frame boundary, not just a no-op.** It clears all `TestingHelper` tracking collections. Test code that inspects recorded draw calls must do so before calling any method that triggers another `Begin()`, or the observations will be lost.

**VSync is not implemented.** `WindowsWindow::SetVSync` is a no-op and `IsVSync()` always returns `false`. No swap-interval API is called. The presentation rate is limited only by `SwapBuffers` in `Dx11Context`.
